4","1625":"1625","England":"England","Portsmouth, Newport, Rhode Island":"Portsmouth, Newport, Rhode Island, United States","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wood","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: mainly a topographic name for someone who lived in or by a wood, from Middle English <i>wode</i> ‘wood’ (Old English <i>wudu</i>). In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, such as French   Bois   and Polish   Les  .","English: in a few cases, a nickname for an eccentric or perhaps a violent person, from Middle English <i>wode</i> ‘frenzied, wild’ (Old English <i>wōd</i>).","Americanized form of French   Gadbois  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Woode","meanings":["(2007: 216; 2010: NA)","English: variant of   Wood  . — Note: The population figure published by the US Census Bureau for this surname in the year 2000 is as high as 312, while the figure for 2010 is supposedly lower than 100."]},{"name":"Bois","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alcide, Antoine, Donat, Marcel, Ovide, Ovila, Raoul, Serge.","French: topographic name for someone living or working in a wood, from (Old) French <i>bois</i> ‘wood’ (from Late Latin <i>boscum</i> ‘bush, shrub, undergrowth’, of ancient Germanic origin), or a habitational name from (Le) Bois, the name of several places in various parts of France. This surname is also found in Haiti. Compare   Debois   and the most frequent French form   Dubois  . Compare also   Boie  ,   Boies  , and   Boyce  .","English: variant of   Boyce   and   Boyes  ."]},{"name":"Woods","meanings":["English: variant of   Wood   with plural or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Irish: adopted as a translation of <b>Ó Cuill</b> ‘descendant of <i>Coll</i>’ (see   Quill  ), or in Ulster of <b>Mac Con Coille</b> ‘son of <i>Cú Choille</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘hound of the wood’, which has also been mistranslated   Cox  , as if formed with <i>coileach</i> ‘cock, rooster’."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705210,"age":10,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705212,"age":30,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705213,"age":52,"year":"1642","toYear":"1651","julianDay":2320789,"title":"The English Civil War","description":"A series of conflicts regarding England's governance during the years 1642 to 1651 is now known as The English Civil War. Charles I summoned supporters to join him against his enemies in Parliament. In October 1642, nearly 10,000 men fought for Charles I and chased Parliament across the River Tamar. Fighting continued for years and was finally ended at the Battle of Worcester on September 3, 1651, with a Parliamentarian victory.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705216,"age":98,"year":"1688","toYear":"1689","julianDay":2337590,"title":"Glorious Revolution","description":"The Glorious Revolution brought the downfall of Catholic King James II and the reign of his Protestant daughter Mary and her Dutch husband, William III of Orange.","url":"http://www.bbc.co.uk/history/british/civil_war_revolution/glorious_revolution_01.shtml","urlTitle":"BBC - Glorious Revolution","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs John Wood was born about 1590, in England. She married John Wood about 1611, in England. They were the parents of at least 5 sons and 2 daughters."},"et":{"about 1590–":"umbes 1590–Surnud","1590–1655":"1590–1655","1612–1664":"1612–1664","1615–1643":"1615–1643","1620–1704":"1620–1704","1622–1654":"1622–1654","1622–1693":"1622–1693","1625–1704":"1625–1704","1635–1696":"1635–1696","1590–Female":"1590–Surnud","about 1590":"umbes 1590","27 Sep 1625":"27. september 1625","1635":"1635","1612":"1612","about 1615":"umbes 1615","1655":"1655","1654":"1654","about 1635":"umbes 1635","1696":"1696","about 1611":"umbes 1611","1651":"1651","about 1612":"umbes 1612","1615":"1615","1693":"1693","1590":"1590","1689":"1689","1622":"1622","1688":"1688","1600":"1600","1643":"1643","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1664":"1664","about 1622":"umbes 1622","about 1620":"umbes 1620","1704":"1704","1625":"1625","England":"England","Portsmouth, Newport, Rhode Island":"Portsmouth, Newport, Rhode Island, Ameerika Ühendriigid"},"fi":{"about 1590–":"noin 1590–Kuollut","1590–1655":"1590–1655","1612–1664":"1612–1664","1615–1643":"1615–1643","1620–1704":"1620–1704","1622–1654":"1622–1654","1622–1693":"1622–1693","1625–1704":"1625–1704","1635–1696":"1635–1696","1590–Female":"1590–Kuollut","about 1590":"noin 1590","27 Sep 1625":"27. syyskuuta 1625","1635":"1635","1612":"1612","about 1615":"noin 1615","1655":"1655","1654":"1654","about 1635":"noin 1635","1696":"1696","about 1